big band type musical ensemble that usually consists ten more musicians with four sections saxophones trumpets trombones and rhythm section Big bands originated during the early 1910s and dominated jazz the early 1940s when swing was most popular The term big band also used describe genre music One problem with this usage that overlooks the variety music played these bands Big bands started accompaniment for dancing contrast with the emphasis improvisation big bands relied written compositions and arrangements They gave greater role bandleaders arrangers and sections instruments rather than soloists Big bands have four sections trumpets trombones saxophones and rhythm section guitar piano double bass and drums The division early big bands was likely two three trumpets one two trombones three saxophones and rhythm section 1930 big bands usually consisted three trumpets three trombones three saxophones and rhythm section four instruments Guitar replaced the banjo and double bass replaced the tuba the 1940s Stan Kentons band and Woody Hermans band used five trumpets four trombones three tenor one bass trombone five saxophones two alto saxophones two tenor saxophones one baritone saxophone and rhythm section exception Duke Ellington who one time used six trumpets Boyd Raeburn drew from symphony orchestras adding his band flute French horn violin and timpani Typical big band arrangements are written strophic form with the same phrase and chord structure repeated several times Each iteration chorus commonly follows twelve bar blues form thirtytwobar AABA song form The first chorus arrangement introduces the melody and followed choruses development This development may take the form improvised solos written soli sections and shout chorusescitation needed arrangements first chorus sometimes preceded introduction which may short few measures may extend chorus its own Many arrangements contain interlude often similar content the introduction inserted between some all choruses Other methods embellishing the form include modulations and cadential extensionscitation needed Some big ensembles like King Olivers played music that was halfarranged halfimprovised often relying head arrangements head arrangement piece music that formed band members during rehearsal They experiment then memorize the way they are going perform the piece without writing sheet music During the 1930s Count Basies band often used head arrangements Basie said just sort start off and the others fall Before 1914 social dance America was dominated steps such the waltz and polka jazz migrated from its New Orleans origin Chicago and New York City energetic suggestive dances traveled with During the next decades ballrooms filled with people doing the jitterbug and Lindy Hop The dance duo Vernon and Irene Castle popularized the foxtrot while accompanied the orchestra James Reese Europe One the first bands accompany the new rhythms was led drummer Art Hickman San Francisco 1916 Hickmans arranger Ferde Grof wrote arrangements which divided the jazz orchestra into sections that combined various ways This intermingling sections became defining characteristic big bands 1919 Paul Whiteman hired Grof use similar techniques for his band Whiteman was educated classical music and called his new bands music symphonic jazz The methods dance bands marked step away from New Orleans jazz With the exception Jelly Roll Morton who continued playing the New Orleans style bandleaders paid attention the demand for dance music and created their own big bands They incorporated elements Broadway Tin Pan Alley ragtime and vaudeville Duke Ellington led his band the Cotton Club Harlem Fletcher Hendersons career started when was persuaded audition for job Club Alabam New York City which eventually turned into job bandleader the Roseland Ballroom these venues which themselves gained notoriety bandleaders and arrangers played greater role than they had before Hickman relied Ferde Grof Whiteman Bill Challi